Nick Scholfield will ride Spring Heeled in the Grand National, replacing his expected mount Sam Winner after trainer Paul Nicholls decided not to commit the horse to the race.  Scholfield will travel to Ireland to familiarize himself with Spring Heeled, who won the Fulke Walwyn Kim Muir Challenge Cup last year and will be one of two horses trained by Jim Culloty in the race.  This decision gives jockey Luke Morris the opportunity to potentially ride Sam Winner if Nicholls decides to run the horse and leaves David Pipe's Soll likely to secure a spot in the race.
Dr. Mehmet Oz's colleagues at Columbia University publicly criticized his television show for promoting unsubstantiated medical claims, arguing that it damages the university's reputation and erodes trust in the medical profession. However, they also defended his position at Columbia, stating that his television persona should not overshadow his accomplishments as a doctor and advocating for clearer guidelines regarding the responsibilities of media physicians. Dr. Oz defended his show, stating that it aims to entertain and promote a "good life" rather than solely focus on medicine, while also criticizing the motives of some of his critics.
The Duchess of Cornwall has launched her own brand of honey, reflecting a growing demand for gourmet honey with unique flavors and origins. The article compares the Duchess's honey to other high-end brands, evaluating their taste, texture, and overall quality based on factors like nectar source and production methods. While some honeys, like the Duchess's and the Vasilissa Greek Honey with Edible Gold Leaf, received high praise, others, like the Welsh Chunk Honeycomb Amphora, proved to be disappointing despite their hefty price tags.
Aubrey de Grey is a controversial biomedical theorist who believes that aging is a disease that can be cured, potentially allowing humans to live for hundreds or even thousands of years. He argues that by repairing and replacing damaged cells and tissues, much like maintaining a vintage car, we can halt and reverse the aging process. While some Silicon Valley billionaires have bought into his theories and fund his research, many scientists dismiss his claims as unrealistic and lacking scientific evidence.
Scientists have developed a new catalyst that significantly improves the efficiency of water electrolysis, a process used to create clean hydrogen fuel. This breakthrough could pave the way for a more sustainable hydrogen economy by enabling the production of hydrogen from renewable energy sources like solar and wind power. The new catalyst minimizes energy loss during the conversion of electricity to hydrogen, making the process more cost-effective and potentially revolutionizing energy storage and use in various applications.
A new study suggests that the iconic Fisher-Price fridge magnets, popular in the 1970s and 1980s, may have influenced the color-letter associations of a significant portion of people with synaesthesia. Researchers found that a notable percentage of synesthetes who grew up exposed to the magnets share the same color pairings for letters as those featured on the toys, indicating a learned component to this neurological condition. While not claiming that the magnets cause synaesthesia, the study highlights the potential impact of external stimuli on shaping sensory experiences for those predisposed to the condition.
Hannah Overton, a Texas mother who spent seven years in prison for the murder of her adopted son, will not face new charges after her conviction was overturned. Nueces County District Attorney Mark Skurka, who had planned to retry Overton, dropped all charges after a review of the case, citing various factors including witness testimonies and medical evidence. Overton, who has always maintained her innocence, celebrated the news with her husband and five children, expressing gratitude for the outcome.
Mary Cartwright, a 91-year-old great-grandmother, recently revisited the Drakelow Shadow Factory where she worked as a wartime scientist during World War II, testing metals for aircraft engines.  The factory, built underground for protection from bombing raids, was a bustling hub of activity where Cartwright worked as the only woman in her department.  After the war, the factory was repurposed for other uses, including a nuclear bunker, and is now owned by a private company, but Cartwright remembers her time there fondly as a unique and valuable experience.
This weekend, top-ranked featherweights Chad Mendes and Ricardo Lamas will fight in a match that could determine the next challenger for the featherweight title, currently held by Jose Aldo. While both fighters acknowledge the skills of their opponent, Mendes believes he is slightly better than Lamas in every aspect and hopes a decisive victory will earn him another shot at Aldo.  Meanwhile, the co-main event features a lightweight bout between Jorge Masvidal and Al Iaquinta, two fighters known for their striking abilities.
An explosion at a paraxylene (PX) plant in Zhangzhou, China, injured six people and caused a large fire. The blast, caused by an oil leak, occurred at an oil storage facility, and while there were no reports of chemical spills, it raised concerns due to the plant's controversial production of the potentially carcinogenic PX. This incident follows a previous explosion at the same plant in 2013 and highlights the ongoing public concern and protests surrounding the construction of PX plants in China.
The MGM Grand in Las Vegas is preparing for an unprecedented influx of visitors for the Mayweather-Pacquiao fight, with expectations of over 100,000 people attending events throughout the weekend. To manage the crowds and ensure safety, the hotel has implemented extensive security measures, including increased staff, restricted access areas, and coordinated efforts with local law enforcement.  The event is anticipated to generate over a billion dollars in revenue for the city, with the MGM Grand maximizing its profits through various avenues like accommodation, food and beverage sales, and of course, gambling.
Samantha Cameron made her first solo appearance of the general election by visiting a school in Rochester and Strood, a Ukip stronghold, in support of Conservative candidate Kelly Tolhurst.  The visit is significant because the Conservatives are desperate to win back the seat from Ukip, which they lost in a by-election last year after Mark Reckless defected from the Tories.  Mrs. Cameron's appearance is part of a larger Conservative strategy to win back voters, which will also include a series of more stridently political interventions from Mrs. Cameron in the coming weeks.
The fatal shooting of Walter Scott, an unarmed black man, by police officer Michael Slager in North Charleston has sparked outrage and highlighted concerns about police conduct. Residents claim the police department dismisses complaints of misconduct, citing a 2013 excessive force complaint against Slager that was dismissed despite witness accounts.  The incident, captured on video, contradicts Slager's initial statement and has led to murder charges against him, raising questions about police accountability and the need for independent review boards.
The Liberal Democrats, expecting to lose a significant number of their 57 seats in the upcoming election, are focusing their campaign on approximately 60 key constituencies.  Despite internal projections showing their numbers potentially dropping to the thirties, the party believes they could still hold the balance of power and form a coalition government.  They remain optimistic about their chances, citing strong campaigning efforts and a belief that national polls don't accurately reflect their support in these targeted areas.
Harry Redknapp, former manager of several Premier League clubs, is open to returning to football management but only if the right opportunity presents itself. Despite receiving a lucrative offer to coach abroad, Redknapp prioritizes being close to his family and would prefer a position where he could help a club achieve promotion or mentor a younger manager.  Redknapp is also a vocal advocate for prostate cancer awareness, having lost a close friend to the disease, and encourages men to get screened.
Moose Toys, a global toy company headquartered in Melbourne, has created a Google-esque work environment to foster creativity and innovation among its employees. The office boasts unique features like a cubby-house meeting room atop a beanstalk, a basketball court, and a pinball machine, encouraging staff to take breaks and engage in fun activities to spark fresh ideas. This approach, emphasizing employee well-being and a vibrant atmosphere, has contributed to the company's success, including winning the 2015 Girl Toy of the Year Award for their Shopkins Small Mart product.
A high-speed passenger train derailed near Split, Croatia, resulting in at least six fatalities and 45 injuries. The train was traveling from Zagreb, the capital, and the incident occurred approximately 12 miles from its destination. An investigation into the cause of the derailment is currently underway.
1. SBS journalist Scott McIntyre was fired for his controversial Anzac Day tweets, which criticized the day and accused Australian soldiers of war crimes. 2. Australian Financial Review writer Geoff Winestock defended McIntyre and echoed his sentiments, calling Anzacs "racist yobs" and Anzac Day a "death cult." 3. While some defended McIntyre's right to free speech, SBS condemned his comments as disrespectful and stated they did not reflect the views of the network, ultimately terminating his employment.
1. In the first week of the 2015 UK election campaign, Labour received £1.9 million in donations, with 84% coming from trade unions, while the Conservatives received £500,000, largely from individuals connected to hedge funds. 2. This significant union funding for Labour, totaling £1.6 million, has fueled criticism that the party is beholden to union bosses and their agendas, particularly regarding policies like raising corporation tax and nationalizing railways. 3. While UKIP received comparatively little in this period, both the Conservatives and Labour have been criticized for unrealistic spending pledges and a lack of transparency regarding how they will address the UK's deficit.
A burglar, Joshua Sweet, broke into a young teacher's home and sexually assaulted her while she slept, leaving her traumatized. Despite the lasting impact on the victim, Judge Mary Stacey sentenced Sweet to a three-year community order, citing his early guilty plea and time served. Victim Support criticized the sentence, arguing that sexual assault, even at the lower end of the sentencing guidelines, requires a punishment that reflects the severity of the crime and delivers justice for the victim.
The shooting death of Walter Scott, an unarmed Black man, by white police officer Michael Slager in Charleston, South Carolina, sparked outrage and grief on social media. Celebrities including Michelle Williams, Janelle Monáe, and Questlove expressed their anger and sadness, while others like Isaiah Washington and Joss Whedon highlighted the need for justice and an end to such tragedies.  The incident, captured on video, showed Slager shooting Scott in the back multiple times as he ran away, contradicting the officer's initial claims and leading to a murder charge against him.
Six gay men in Baghdad were killed in two separate shootings by members of their own tribe in the past 10 days. The victims were targeted after being disowned by their families and a tribal meeting where members decided to go after them. A cafe known as a gathering place for gay people in Sadr City was also set on fire.
A pink, ruby-encrusted Hermes Birkin bag is on sale for £140,000, making it potentially the most expensive handbag in Britain. The bag's rarity and exclusivity make it a desirable collector's item that experts believe is a good investment, unlike cars which depreciate in value. Hermes bags are renowned for their quality craftsmanship, heritage, and limited supply, contributing to their high price tag and popularity among celebrities and collectors.
Wladimir Klitschko, the world heavyweight boxing champion, is deeply concerned about the ongoing conflict in his home country of Ukraine, which he believes was unjustly attacked by Russia. Despite the ongoing crisis, which has caused immense suffering and loss of life, Klitschko remains optimistic about Ukraine's future as a democratic nation with the support of the international community. While preparing for his upcoming title defense, Klitschko remains connected to the situation in Ukraine through his brother, Vitali, and personal visits, emphasizing his commitment to both his sport and his country's well-being.
Bruce Jenner's upcoming eight-episode docu-series on E! will chronicle his transition into a woman, but his sons and stepdaughter Kim Kardashian are worried he's revealing too much. They believe the Diane Sawyer interview was tasteful and impactful, and they've urged him to finish the process privately, fearing the docu-series will cheapen his accomplishment. Despite their concerns, Bruce is committed to the project, believing it will educate people and create empathy by showing the reality of his journey.
Robert Downey Jr. walked out of an interview with Channel 4 news presenter Krishnan Guru-Murthy after being asked about his past struggles with drug addiction. Guru-Murthy's line of questioning, which Downey Jr. found too personal, has prompted comparisons to other celebrity interview walkouts, including those by Naomi Campbell, Justin Bieber, and Rihanna, all of whom cut interviews short after being asked about sensitive topics.  These incidents highlight the tension between celebrities' desire for privacy and the public's interest in their personal lives, often fueled by intrusive interview questions.
The Yarmouk refugee camp in Damascus, Syria, has fallen under the control of ISIS, leading to widespread atrocities and displacement. Refugees who escaped the camp report witnessing horrific acts of violence, including beheadings and the killing of children in front of their parents. A 16-year-old boy recounted seeing ISIS militants playing football with a severed head, highlighting the brutality inflicted upon the camp's residents.
Millwall defeated Wigan Athletic 2-0 in a heated Championship match crucial to both teams' fight against relegation.  Martyn Waghorn's red card for Wigan in the second half gave Millwall the momentum to score through Jimmy Abdou and, later, Magaye Gueye.  The win keeps Millwall's survival hopes alive while putting Wigan in a more precarious position, with manager Gary Caldwell frustrated by his team's performance and Millwall's physical approach.
British workers who buy their lunch spend an average of £1,840 a year, but could save £1,300 by preparing food at home. The article suggests numerous lunch ideas, from simple cheese and crackers to more elaborate Vietnamese banh mi sandwiches and steamed Chinese buns, emphasizing that homemade lunches can be delicious, affordable, and convenient.  It also provides recipes for budget-friendly meals like feta and vegetable bake, crispy mash hash, pea and ham frittata, and spring chicken casserole, demonstrating that saving money doesn't mean sacrificing taste or nutrition.
For £3,500, Natural World Safaris offers a rare seven-day trip to Russia's Durminskoye Reserve, where tourists can experience the Siberian tiger's natural habitat and assist in conservation efforts. While sightings of the endangered Siberian tiger are not guaranteed, guests will work alongside conservationist Alexander Batalov to track tigers, set camera traps, and contribute to the protection of this elusive species. Although the accommodations are basic, the opportunity to explore the tigers' domain and support their survival makes this trip a once-in-a-lifetime experience.
A 24-year-old Algerian jihadi, Sid Ahmed Ghlam, was arrested in Paris after accidentally shooting himself in the leg. Police investigations revealed Ghlam was planning an imminent attack on churches in Paris under the orders of ISIS and was linked to the murder of 33-year-old Aurelie Chatelain. This foiled attack comes amidst heightened security in France following the Charlie Hebdo attacks in January.
A study on the microbiome of the uncontacted Yanomami people in the Amazon revealed they have the most diverse gut bacteria ever recorded in humans, highlighting the impact of modern lifestyles on our own microbiomes. This discovery suggests that Western diets and practices may be depleting beneficial bacteria, and studying isolated populations could offer insights into developing new medical treatments. Interestingly, the Yanomami microbiome also showed antibiotic resistance despite no prior exposure, indicating that such resistance may be a natural occurrence in some bacteria, amplified by antibiotic overuse in modern society.
Protests against statues and memorials of figures tied to South Africa's colonial past have erupted across the country, with many being defaced or vandalized. The protests were sparked by the removal of a statue of Cecil Rhodes from the University of Cape Town after it was deemed offensive to black students. While the government supports the removal of colonial symbols, some white solidarity groups oppose it, leading to increased racial tensions and debates about historical legacy.
Lizzi Crawford, a 32-year-old mother of six, was inspired to lose over 7 stone after a child on a bus mistook her for being pregnant.  Lizzi had previously lived an unhealthy lifestyle, consuming a diet high in takeaways and alcohol, but she committed to a healthier lifestyle by cooking nutritious meals and attending fitness classes.  Despite facing a cervical cancer diagnosis in 2012, Lizzi successfully lost weight and now enjoys improved physical and mental well-being, crediting her supportive gym community for her success.
Nafir Afzal, Britain's most senior Muslim prosecutor, warns that hundreds of British teenagers are being radicalized by ISIS, viewing them as "pop idols" similar to One Direction and Justin Bieber. He argues that ISIS propaganda effectively markets a glamorous image to these youths, who are then manipulated and groomed similar to victims of sexual predators. Afzal urges for a new approach to combatting radicalization, advocating for young Muslim role models to counter ISIS's messaging and prevent future terrorist attacks.
Paul Downton was sacked as managing director of the England Cricket Board following England's poor performance in the Cricket World Cup and other questionable decisions made during his tenure.  The ECB will replace Downton's position with a new "director of England Cricket" role that will focus on performance and accountability.  Former England captain Michael Vaughan and former captain Andrew Strauss are potential candidates for the new director position.
James Haskell, captain of the London Wasps rugby team, celebrated the release of Avengers: Age of Ultron by posting a photo of himself dressed as Iron Man on Instagram. Haskell, who rejoined the Wasps in 2012 after playing for teams in France, Japan, and New Zealand, has made over 100 appearances for the club and has earned 57 caps playing for England.  The premiere of the highly anticipated Avengers sequel took place at Westfield London shopping centre, with fans gathering to see stars like Robert Downey Jr., Chris Hemsworth, and Scarlett Johansson.
Good Morning Britain launched the #SelfieEsteem campaign to encourage body positivity by asking celebrities and viewers to share their first unfiltered selfie. The campaign was inspired by a survey revealing that women take an average of six selfies before posting one online due to pressure to look good on social media, highlighting widespread self-esteem issues.  Many celebrities participated, including Susanna Reid, Josie Gibson, and Piers Morgan, sharing unfiltered photos and personal anecdotes about struggling with self-esteem.
Imran Uddin, a 25-year-old science student at the University of Birmingham, was sentenced to four months in jail for using keyboard spying devices to hack into university computers and inflate his grades. Uddin used the stolen staff passwords to access the university's grading system and changed his marks on five assignments, raising one grade from a 57% to a 73%. The judge emphasized the need for deterrence, stating that Uddin's actions could undermine public trust in the academic system.
Hillary Clinton and her husband Bill took a break from campaigning and enjoyed a leisurely stroll near their Chappaqua home, while her campaign vans were serviced at a local body shop. Clinton is scheduled to resume campaigning in New Hampshire with events at a family-owned business and a community college. Despite attempts to connect with "everyday" Americans, Clinton continues to face scrutiny for her wealth and perceived elitism, highlighted by recent incidents that were criticized as staged and inauthentic.
Six Leeds players withdrew from a crucial match citing injuries, a move that former captain Trevor Cherry called "disgraceful" and indicative of the larger chaos engulfing the club.  Striker Steve Morison, while surprised by the players' actions, acknowledged the constant turmoil surrounding Leeds, stating he'd "never known anything like it in football."  The incident is just the latest in a string of controversies plaguing Leeds, including managerial instability and the impending return of banned club president Massimo Cellino.
Green Party leader Natalie Bennett is facing scrutiny due to controversial blog posts made by her boyfriend, Jim Jepps, on his personal blog "The Daily Maybe." Jepps' blog, which he maintained until 2011, contained posts defending "rape fantasies," describing pedophiles as "complex human beings," and questioning the inclusion of teachers who have relationships with students on the sex offenders registry. The Green Party has distanced itself from Jepps' remarks, stating that they do not endorse his views and that he has not been a member of the party since 2012.
Heather Mack, accused of murdering her mother in Bali, has agreed to transfer a significant portion of her $1.3 million trust fund to her newborn daughter, Stella, for her care and living expenses.  Mack and her boyfriend, Tommy Schaefer, are awaiting sentencing after prosecutors recommended 15 years for Mack and 18 years for Schaefer, sparing them the death penalty due to their remorse and the needs of their child.  While awaiting sentencing, Mack and Schaefer are caring for Stella in their respective prison cells, with Mack planning to breastfeed for two years and keep Stella with her in prison until she turns two.
The article discusses the growing accusations against the North Charleston police department for a potential cover-up in the shooting of Walter Scott by officer Michael Slager. Discrepancies exist between the official police report and the bystander video, including claims of CPR being administered and the positioning of the Taser, suggesting a potential attempt to tamper with the scene. Public figures and media commentators are expressing concern over the incident, highlighting a potential pattern of police misconduct and the importance of the video evidence in bringing the truth to light.
Marouane Fellaini has gone from being criticized by Manchester United fans to being one of the team's most important players, earning praise from teammate Wayne Rooney. After a difficult first season at Old Trafford, Fellaini has thrived under manager Louis van Gaal, who is utilizing him as a second striker to great effect. Fellaini's strength and aerial ability have been crucial in United's recent victories, and his teammates believe his hard work and dedication are finally paying off.
This year's FA Cup semi-finals, held at Wembley Stadium, provided thrilling football and memorable moments for television viewers. Despite initial criticism about the venue and scheduling, both matches delivered exciting action and captivating storylines, including Reading's valiant effort against Arsenal and the emotional farewell for Liverpool's Steven Gerrard. The combination of compelling football, engaging commentary, and behind-the-scenes glimpses solidified the FA Cup semi-finals as a must-watch event.
Reading, who haven't reached the FA Cup semi-final in 88 years, are preparing to face a tough challenge against in-form Arsenal at Wembley. Manager Steve Clarke, while acknowledging the magnitude of the occasion and Arsenal's strength, has urged his players to treat it like any other game and focus on executing their game plan. Despite being considered heavy underdogs, Clarke believes that a "perfect game" from his side could see them overcome Arsenal and make history by reaching the FA Cup final for the first time.
A severe HIV outbreak in rural Indiana, linked to the sharing of needles among users of the prescription opioid Opana, has resulted in 142 positive HIV cases in a sparsely populated area. The outbreak has prompted a public health emergency declaration, increased resources and education efforts, and a temporary needle exchange program to combat the spread of the disease. Health officials warn that this outbreak serves as a reminder of the dangers of injection drug use and the importance of vigilance in preventing the spread of HIV and other infectious diseases.
Jeremy Clarkson will not face prosecution for his attack on a Top Gear producer, as the victim, Oisin Tymon, declined to press charges. Despite this, the BBC fired Clarkson from Top Gear, though he will still appear in upcoming live shows with co-hosts Richard Hammond and James May. The future of Top Gear remains uncertain, with speculation surrounding the potential departure of Hammond, May, and show boss Andy Wilman.
Six U.S. Navy guards at Camp Bucca, Iraq, have been charged with assaulting detainees in May. The charges stem from incidents that left two detainees with minor bruises and another where eight prisoners were confined overnight in a cell sprayed with riot control agent.  The six guards will face courts-martial within 30 days at Camp Bucca.
1. After being found guilty on all counts, the Boston Marathon bombing trial shifted to the sentencing phase, where victims and their families gave emotional testimonies about the devastating impact of the attack. 2. Jurors heard heartbreaking stories of loss, grief, and resilience from those who lost loved ones and those who suffered life-altering injuries, including amputations and the constant struggle of recovery. 3. Prosecutors aimed to portray the human cost of Tsarnaev's actions, highlighting the innocence of the victims and the lasting pain and trauma inflicted by the bombings, while the defense will present their case for a life sentence instead of the death penalty.
11-year-old Charlie Patino, a talented midfielder playing for Luton Town's academy, has received offers from top Premier League clubs Arsenal, Chelsea, and Tottenham.  Similar to Jack Wilshere, who was also scouted from Luton at a young age, Patino's family is carefully considering the offers before making a decision at the end of the season.  Despite the attention, Patino remains grounded, committed to his development, and supported by both his family and Luton Town in navigating this significant opportunity.
A Bangkok Airways plane crashed while landing at Koh Samui airport in Thailand, resulting in the pilot's death and 37 injuries. The ATR-72 turboprop, carrying 68 passengers and four crew members, skidded off the runway after the pilot received warnings about strong winds.  Seven people sustained serious injuries, and rescue efforts were underway to free the trapped co-pilot.
Emmanuel Adebayor has refuted rumors of an impending transfer, stating his desire to remain with Tottenham and compete for his position. Despite a decline in form and limited playing time due to Harry Kane's emergence, Adebayor expressed his contentment playing in the Premier League, calling it the world's best.  He aims to fulfill his contract with the club despite only making 16 appearances and scoring two goals this season.
